sols_latex:
In this case we need to use logarithmic differentiation, indeed it is
impossible to use the power rule since there is an $x^2$ as exponent. We
cannot differentiate it in the same way we do for exponential functions
since we take the power of \emph{x} and not \emph{e} or another
constant. Hence we need to use logarithmic differentiation. First set

\begin{align*}
y=x^{(x^2)},
\end{align*} then taking the logarithm on both sides we find

\begin{align*}
\ln y = \ln (x^{(x^2)}) = x^2 \ln(x).
\end{align*} Now keeping in mind that
\emph{y} is a function of \emph{x}, we can take the derivatives on both
sides and get

\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dx} \ln y = \frac{d}{dx} (x^2 \ln(x)) .
\end{align*} The left-hand side
is simply

\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dx} \ln y = \frac{1}{y} \cdot \frac{d}{dx} y = \frac{1}{y} y',
\end{align*}
while the right-hand side gives, using the product rule,

\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dx}(x^2 \ln(x)) = 2x \ln(x) + x^2 \frac{1}{x} =  2x \ln(x) + x.
\end{align*}
Putting everything back together, we get

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{y} y' = 2x \ln(x) + x,
\end{align*} and thus

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle y' = y (2x \ln(x) + x).
\end{align*} Replacing \emph{y} by
$x^{(x^2)},$ we finally get

\begin{align*}
y' = x^{(x^2)} ( 2x \ln(x) + x).
\end{align*}

